title.narrative: 1.2 HEALTH SYSTEMS STRENGTHENING

description.narrative: The four health system component elements (Human resource, HMIS, Supply chain and logistics and health financing) for effective and efficient delivery of services are in place and operational, which contributes to Child Health, Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Maternal And Newborn Health, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2020, increased proportions of Somalis, especially mothers and children, have equitable access to and use essential health services in targeted areas

description.narrative: UNICEF supported the respective Ministries of Health in conducting a human-resources for health evaluation, the day-to-day DHIS2/LMIS (District Health Information Systems/Logistics Management Information Systems) management and the ongoing DHIS indicator review. The HR evaluation assessed the current incentive arrangements for MoH staff, which resulted in MoH employees no longer receiving multiple incentives from different resources because staff incentive details are transparently available via the UN Somalia Capacity Reporting Injection Tool (CIRT). DHIS2 reporting rates improved by 11% from 2018 and the indicator review will add improved automated dashboards, scorecards and reports in 2021 to enhance the use of data | Status:Met | As-of Date:03/01/2021
